The paper deals with the estimation of achievable rates in wireless networks, which is a problem in information theory (cs.IT). The focus is on device-to-device communications, which falls under the category of networking and internet architecture (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of compressive sensing techniques, which is a topic in signal processing and machine learning (cs.SI). The application of the framework to sparse or low rank representations of the composite channel gain matrix suggests a connection to matrix completion and matrix factorization problems, which are topics in multimedia (cs.MM) and machine learning (cs.LG).
